docs.abstract: The Trump administration is expected to indict hackers and roll out import restrictions out of concern that Beijing will not easily change its trade, cyber and economic practices.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration is expected to indict hackers and roll out import restrictions out of concern that Beijing will not easily change its trade, cyber and economic practices.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The cyberattack on the Marriott hotel chain that collected personal details of roughly 500 million guests was part of a Chinese intelligence-gathering effort that also hacked health insurers and the security clearance files of millions more Americans, according to two people briefed on the investigation.

headline.main: Marriott Data Breach Is Traced to Chinese Hackers as U.S. Readies Crackdown on Beijing
headline.print_headline: Marriott Data Breach Traced to Chinese Hackers

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Having lost in two federal courts and fearing more setbacks, the Trump administration is revising rules that allow employers to deny women insurance coverage for contraceptives based on religious or moral objections.

headline.main: Trump Administration to Revise Birth Control Exemptions in Hopes of Saving Them

docs.abstract: With Democrats seen as likely to retake the House, drug makers are quietly making contingency plans to fend off proposals that would squeeze their profits.
docs.snippet: With Democrats seen as likely to retake the House, drug makers are quietly making contingency plans to fend off proposals that would squeeze their profits.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The pharmaceutical industry, pilloried by President Trump for the last two years, is war-gaming for the possibility that its worst fear is realized: that Democrats, if they flip control of the House, find common ground with the president to rein in drug prices.

headline.main: What Big Pharma Fears Most: A Trump Alliance With Democrats to Cut Drug Prices
headline.print_headline: Big Pharma’s Nightmare: Trump Crossing the Aisle to Curb Drug Prices

docs.abstract: The Federal Trade Commission said a Florida enterprise collected millions with a deceptive marketing scheme aimed at Americans searching for health coverage.
docs.snippet: The Federal Trade Commission said a Florida enterprise collected millions with a deceptive marketing scheme aimed at Americans searching for health coverage.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal authorities have shut down a network of Florida companies that they say used aggressive, deceptive tactics to sell skimpy health insurance products that skirt requirements of the Affordable Care Act and left tens of thousands of people around the country with unpaid medical bills.

headline.main: Federal Officials Shut Down Sales of ‘Ruinous’ Health Insurance Plans
headline.print_headline: Federal Authorities Shut Down Seller of ‘Ruinous’ Health Insurance Plans

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — States around the country are clamping down on pharmaceutical companies, forcing them to disclose and justify price increases, but the drug manufacturers are fighting back, challenging the state laws as a violation of their constitutional rights.

docs.abstract: New work requirements imposed on the state’s Medicaid recipients have left 4,350 low-income residents without health coverage. “I hope these data scare the pants off people,” a panel member said.
docs.snippet: New work requirements imposed on the state’s Medicaid recipients have left 4,350 low-income residents without health coverage. “I hope these data scare the pants off people,” a panel member said.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Members of a federal advisory panel expressed alarm this week that 4,350 low-income people in Arkansas had lost Medicaid coverage because they failed to show they were complying with new work requirements held up by the Trump administration as a model for the nation.

headline.main: Federal Panel Alarmed as Thousands Are Dropped From Medicaid in Arkansas
headline.print_headline: Advisers Sound an Alarm After Thousands Are Dropped From Medicaid

docs.abstract: The appointment of Mark Calabria, who is Vice President Mike Pence’s chief economist, to run the Federal Housing Finance Agency would come at a sensitive moment for the United States housing market.
docs.snippet: The appointment of Mark Calabria, who is Vice President Mike Pence’s chief economist, to run the Federal Housing Finance Agency would come at a sensitive moment for the United States housing market.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump is expected to nominate Mark Calabria, the chief economist for Vice President Mike Pence, to run the government agency overseeing the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, according to two White House officials.

headline.main: Trump May Choose Critic of Fannie and Freddie to Lead Agency Overseeing Them
headline.print_headline: As Housing Wobbles, Trump Eyes Critic of Fannie and Freddie to Oversee Them

docs.abstract: President Trump tried to recapture his administration’s narrative, warning that if his supporters did not vote, he would be subjected to impeachment.
docs.snippet: President Trump tried to recapture his administration’s narrative, warning that if his supporters did not vote, he would be subjected to impeachment.
docs.lead_paragraph: BILLINGS, Mont. — President Trump tried on Thursday to tamp down perceptions of an out-of-control White House, after a string of devastating reports about his insurgent staff, warning supporters here that if they did not turn out to vote in November, his political enemies would subject him to impeachment.

headline.main: ‘I’m Winning,’ Trump Tells Montana Crowd as He Tries to Regain Control Amid Turmoil
headline.print_headline: Trump, at Montana Rally, Tells Crowd: ‘I’m Winning’
